Interaction model

library(broom)
score_model_interaction <- lm(score ~ age * gender, data = evals_ch6)
tidy(score_model_interaction)

In an interaction model like this, the reqgression lines \[\hat{y} = \widehat{score} = b_0 + b_\textrm{age} \cdot \textrm{age} + b_\textrm{male} \cdot 1_\textrm{is male}(x) + b_\textrm{age,male} \cdot \textrm{age} \cdot 1_\textrm{is male}(x)\] As was the case with the model using a single categorical explanatory variable, the indicator term \(1_\textrm{is male}(x)\) zeroes out if the record is not male. The interaction effect, \(b_\textrm{age,male}\) is age:gendermale from the regression table. This term indicates the extent to which one variable (age) depends on another (gender)

Thus the equation for the female line is:

\[\hat{y} = \widehat{score} = 4.883 - .018 \cdot age\] Whereas for males its: \[ \hat{y} = \widehat{score} = (4.883 - .446) + (-.018 + 0.014) \cdot age \\ = 4.437 - 0.004 \cdot age \]

Parallel slopes

In an interaction model, the explanatory variables can behave differently across groups. In the age * gender model, the age penalty for men was significantly lower for men than for women.

In a parallel slopes model, only the intercept varies. Rather than age * gender, the model is age + gender.

score_model_parallel_slopes <- lm(score ~ age + gender, data = evals_ch6)
tidy(score_model_parallel_slopes)
score_model_parallel_slopes %>% 
  augment() %>% 
  ggplot(aes(x = age, y = score, color = gender)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_line(aes(y = .fitted))

Residuals

score_model_interaction %>% 
  augment() %>% 
  select(score, age, gender, .fitted, .resid)
score_model_parallel_slopes %>% 
  augment() %>% 
  select(score, age, gender, .fitted, .resid)

Regression Plane

debt_model <- lm(debt ~ credit_limit + income, data = credit_ch6)
tidy(debt_model)

Even though credit limit and income are separately positively correlated with debt, they are jointly negatively correlated. This is Simpsons paradox, which states that adding an additional variable to a model can reverse or negate a trend observed before adding the new variable.
